    {
        "type": "theory",
        "title": "ðŸ“š Use of the prefix 'ja' in dholuo.",
        "content": {
          "introduction": "In Dholuo, the prefix 'ja-' is used to indicate a person associated with or a person who does something. It's similar to using 'person of'"
          }
        },
    {
        "type": "table",
        "title": "ðŸ“š Use of 'ja' to indicate a person's origin.", 
        "content": {
            "introduction": "You can use the prefix 'ja' to indicate a person's origin. It changes to 'Jo' for its plural form.:",
            "columns": ["Dholuo (Singular)", "English (Singular)", "Dholuo (Plural)", "English (Plural)"],
            "rows": [
                ["Jaseme", "A person from a place called 'Seme'", "Joseme", "People from Seme"],
                ["Jagem", "A person from a place called 'Gem'", "Jogem", "People from Gem"],
                ["Jakenya", "A Kenyan", "Jokenya", "Kenyans"],
                ["Jaamerica", "An American", "Joamerica", "Americans"],
                ["Japiny", "A person of the world", "Jopiny", "People of the world."]
              ],
            "grammar_note": "When used to indicate citizenship/origin, the prefix 'ja' is used only for men. For women, the prefix 'nyar' meaning 'daughter of' is used. It changes to 'nyi' meaning 'daughters of'. So you would say 'nyar seme' and 'nyi seme' to describe women coming from Seme."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "table",
            "title": "ðŸ“š Nouns and Their Plurals", 
            "content": {
                "introduction": "You can also use the prefix 'ja' to indicate a person's profession",
                "columns": ["Dholuo (Singular)", "English (Singular)", "Dholuo (Plural)", "English (Plural)"],
                "rows": [
                    ["Jalweny", "A soldier ('lweny' means 'war')", "Jolweny", "Soldiers"],
                    ["Ja ohala", "A businessman ('ohala' means 'business')", "Jo ohala", "Businessmen"],
                    ["Ja ng'ad bura", "A judge.", "Jo ng'ad bura", "Judges"],
                    ["Jatelo", "A leader ('telo' is 'to lead'.)", "Jotelo", "Leaders"],
                    ["Jathieth", "A doctor ('thieth' is 'to cure'.)", "Jothieth", "Doctors"],
                    ["Jaot", "A spouse ('ot' means 'house'). So you're literally saying 'the person of my house' to refer to your spouse.", "Joot", "Spouses"]
                  ],
                "grammar_note": ""
                }
              },
        {
            "type": "table",
            "title": "ðŸ“š Nouns and Their Plurals", 
            "content": {
                "introduction": "You can also use the prefix 'ja' to describe a person's characteristics",
                "columns": ["Dholuo (Singular)", "English (Singular)", "Dholuo (Plural)", "English (Plural)"],
                "rows": [
                    ["Jarachar", "A white person ('rachar' meaning 'white')", "Jorochere", "White people. (Here 'ja' turns to 'jo' and 'rachar' turns to 'rochere' to make the plural form. It's a double plural."],
                    ["Jarateng'", "A black person ('rateng'' meaning 'black')", "Jorotenge", "Black people. (Another double plural)"],
                    ["Jarikni", "A fast/hurried person ('rikni' meaning 'to hurry')", "Jorikni", "Hurried people."],
                    ["Jasamwoyo", "A lazy person ('samwoyo' is 'laziness').", "Josamwoyo", "Lazy people"]
